    en: "NY has the strongest wage-theft recovery scheme in the country outside a small number of jurisdictions. The core rules are in Article 6 of the NY Labor Law. The remedies in NY Labor Law § 198 can double the unpaid amount, add attorneys' fees, and extend criminal liability to the employer's officers. What counts as wage theft. NY treats all of the following as unpaid wages under Article 6: unpaid straight-time hours (including off-the-clock work before or after a shift), unpaid overtime at 1.5 times the regular rate for hours above 40 in a workweek under 12 NYCRR 142, illegal deductions from pay under NY Labor Law § 193 (for cash register shortages, breakage, uniforms, or anything else not expressly authorized in writing for the employee's benefit), stolen tips retained by the employer or shared with managers and owners in violation of NY Labor Law § 196-d, paychecks that bounce, final paychecks withheld after termination, and wage theft by misclassification — labeling an employee as a 1099 independent contractor to avoid minimum wage, overtime, unemployment insurance, and workers' compensation obligations. Frequency-of-pay rule. Under NY Labor Law § 191, manual workers (construction, cleaning, retail stocking, delivery, and similar physical work) must be paid weekly and no later than 7 days after the end of the pay period. Clerical and other non-manual workers must be paid at least semi-monthly. Violations of the frequency-of-pay rule create a private right of action under § 198 after the NY Court of Appeals decision in Vega v. CM & Associates Construction Management. Wage notice and paystub requirements. NY Labor Law § 195 requires an employer to give each employee a written wage notice at hire and a detailed pay stub with every payment. The notice must state the rate of pay, the basis (hourly, salary, piece rate), the regular pay day, and the employer's legal name and address. A failure to provide a proper wage notice creates statutory damages of $50 per workday up to $5,000 per employee, plus costs and attorneys' fees. A failure to provide a compliant pay stub creates statutory damages of $250 per workday up to $5,000 per employee. Recovery of unpaid wages. Under NY Labor Law § 198(3), claims for unpaid wages can reach back 6 years. A successful claim recovers the unpaid amount plus liquidated damages equal to 100 percent of the unpaid amount (unless the employer proves a good-faith basis to believe the underpayment was lawful), plus prejudgment interest, plus reasonable attorneys' fees. If the judgment is not paid within 90 days, the statute adds 15 percent of the unpaid judgment as an additional penalty. Retaliation protection. NY Labor Law § 215 prohibits firing, reducing hours, reporting to immigration authorities, threatening, or otherwise retaliating against an employee for making a wage complaint. A retaliation finding supports reinstatement, back pay, and civil penalties up to $20,000. Retaliating against a complaint is itself a Class B misdemeanor. Criminal liability. NY Labor Law § 198-a makes wage theft a criminal offense. A first conviction is a misdemeanor punishable by a fine of $500 to $20,000 and up to one year in jail. A second conviction within 6 years is a felony. The 2023 Wage Theft Accountability Act amendment to NY Penal Law § 155 also allows district attorneys to aggregate multiple underpayments into a single larceny charge, making grand larceny prosecutions available for larger wage-theft schemes. NY DOL enforcement. The NY Department of Labor Division of Labor Standards investigates wage-theft complaints under Article 6 through its Wage Theft Hub at dol.ny.gov/wage-theft-hub or by phone at [number being verified]. DOL can issue a stipulation for back wages, assess civil penalties, and refer cases to the attorney general for criminal prosecution. Under the 2025-2026 state budget DOL also has expanded tools to place liens on an employer's property, seize funds, and issue work-stoppage orders against businesses with repeated violations. Private lawsuit. An employee can bypass the DOL and sue directly in state court under NY Labor Law § 198 or in federal court under the federal Fair Labor Standards Act (29 USC § 216(b)). Federal FLSA has a 2-year statute of limitations (3 years for willful violations), while NY Labor Law extends to 6 years. Most NY wage cases are filed under state law because of the longer window and higher damages. Misclassification cases. A worker labeled 1099 who was really performing employee work can file a Form SS-8 request with the IRS for a federal misclassification determination or file directly with the NY DOL. The NY Construction Industry Fair Play Act, NY Labor Law § 861 and following, creates a presumption that a construction-industry worker is an employee unless the employer proves independent-contractor status."
